Carefully restored in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1957</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC">Great Wall</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Badaling</ENAMEX>, <NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">67 km</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">42 miles</NUMEX>) northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Beijing</ENAMEX>, is the most-visited portion of the wall. The mountain setting is spectacular and the wall rises and falls steeply as it winds up and down the ridges. <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">About 7</NUMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">m</ENAMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">24</NUMEX> ft) high and <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">5 m</ENAMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">18</NUMEX> ft) wide, this <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ming Dynasty</ENAMEX> fortification is built of tamped earth, stone, and brick. <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC">Beacon</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC_DESC">towers</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">stone</ENAMEX> and brick are mounted at regular intervals. It is possible to walk the stairs of the restored section for <NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">about 2 km</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">11‚ÅÑ2 miles</NUMEX>) before reaching the crumbling remains of the original wall on either end. At the northern terminus, there is a cable car connecting the wall to a parking lot below. The parking <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC_DESC">lots</ENAMEX> at the base of the wall are filled with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">vendors</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">stores</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">restaurants</ENAMEX>, and other modern attractions, including a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">cinema</ENAMEX> and a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">KFC</ENAMEX> fast-food outlet.
